  "text": "Since the actual signals for a human's joint angles are hard to obtain with the above control mechanism alone, we introduce a conversion mechanism for angular positions to imitate the waveform of motion-capture data. We first determine the value of the stiffness parameter ki so that the frequency of the angular position e i coincides with those of the motion data. Next, the signals generated at the controller are distributed in mUltiple modes. The h-th mode signal, denoted by 1l 7, is composed by blending the angular e i and velocity Wi signals with a phase control parameter <1>7 as, then the conversion is given by [CITATION_1] where qi denotes the joint angle corresponding to the i-th controller. The phase <1>7, the coefficients a7, and delay parameters M are simultaneously computed to minimize the sum of the squared differences between motion-capture signals and the resulting waveform qi, where these values are sought in the secondorder approximation (Nh = 2). It is noteworthy that the accuracy of an approximation can be arbitrarily improved by increasing the order N h, but the higher frequencies produced as a by-product tend to cause unnatural bodily vibrations. Moreover, human visual perception is usually insensitive to the high-frequency component of movements. Furthermore, motion-capture data inevitably include noise components produced in measuring and transforming the data. For these reasons, we experimentally found that the second order approximation effectively balances accuracy with smoothness for our locomotive examples.",
